usage = UsageSection(
    content="HDR (Harness Done Right) is an easy-to-use Python library that lets you formalize any task as code and validate its completion using LLM-powered assertions. No prior experience with LLM tools or advanced Python is required - follow this complete, step-by-step guide to get started:\n\n### Key Concepts Explained\nBefore we begin, let's clarify a few basic terms you'll see throughout the guide:\n- **BaseModel**: This is the parent class all your task classes will inherit from. It provides automatic runtime type checking, so you don't have to write validation code for input/output values yourself.\n- **llm_assert()**: A special HDR function that uses AI to validate natural language conditions about your task. It only passes when the AI is 100% confident your requirement is met.\n- **quote()**: A security function that safely wraps values when you use them in `llm_assert()` statements, preventing prompt injection attacks.\n\n### Step 1: Install HDR\nSet up HDR on your computer in 6 simple steps:\n1. Clone the official HDR repository from GitHub: `git clone https://github.com/hdr-project/hdr.git`\n2. Navigate to the HDR skill directory: `cd hdr/hdr-skill`\n3. Create a Python virtual environment (this keeps HDR dependencies separate from your other projects): `python3 -m venv .venv`\n4. Activate the virtual environment:\n   - On Linux or Mac: `source .venv/bin/activate`\n   - On Windows: `.venv\\Scripts\\activate`\n5. Install required dependencies: `pip install openai pytest pydantic locache`\n6. Install the HDR library: `cd scripts && pip install -e .`\n\n### Step 2: Configure Your API Key\nHDR uses OpenRouter to access LLMs. Get an API key from https://openrouter.ai first, then configure it using the built-in `save_config` function:\n```python\nfrom hdr import save_config\nsave_config({\n    \"openrouter_api_key\": \"paste-your-openrouter-api-key-here\",\n    \"openrouter_model\": \"anthropic/claude-3-opus\" # You can use any model listed on openrouter.ai\n})\n```\n\n### Step 3: Define Your Task\nCreate a Python class for your task. This class describes what your task does and what conditions must be met for it to be complete. Let's create a simple text summarization task as an example:\n\n```python\n# First import the HDR tools we need\nfrom hdr import BaseModel, llm_assert, quote\n\n# Define your task class - always inherit from BaseModel\nclass SummarizeText(BaseModel):\n    # Define your task's input and output fields with type annotations\n    original_text: str  # Input: the text you want to summarize\n    summary: str        # Output: the summarized text\n    max_words: int = 50 # Optional parameter with a default value\n    \n    def __init__(self, **data):\n        # Call the parent constructor first to run automatic type checks\n        super().__init__(**data)\n        \n        # Add your validation conditions using llm_assert()\n        # Always wrap values in quote() for security\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} includes all important information from {quote(self.original_text)}\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} is no more than {self.max_words} words long\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} is written in simple, easy to understand language\")\n```\n\n### Step 4: Run Your Task\nTo execute your task, just create an instance of your class:\n- Pass all required values as parameters\n- If your task depends on other tasks, pass those task instances as parameters too\n- All type checks and LLM validations run automatically when you create the instance\n- If no errors are thrown, your task is 100% complete and validated!\n\n```python\n# Run your task by creating an instance of the class\nresult = SummarizeText(\n    original_text=\"HDR is a new Python library that makes it easy to define tasks and validate that they were completed correctly. It uses AI to check your work automatically, so you can be confident that your tasks meet all your requirements. HDR works with any LLM model and requires no complicated setup.\",\n    summary=\"HDR is a Python library that uses AI to automatically validate task completion, working with any LLM model and requiring minimal setup.\",\n    max_words=30\n)\n\n# If you get to this line, your task was successful!\nprint(\"🎉 Task complete!\")\nprint(f\"Original text length: {len(result.original_text)}\")\nprint(f\"Summary: {result.summary}\")\nprint(f\"Summary length: {len(result.summary)}\")\n```\n\nHDR automatically saves the results of LLM calls, so you can run your code multiple times without paying for duplicate API calls.",
    code_examples=[
        "# Complete end-to-end example: HDR setup and text summarization task\n# Follow these exact steps to run this example:\n# 1. Clone HDR: git clone https://github.com/hdr-project/hdr.git\n# 2. Install: cd hdr/hdr-skill && python3 -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate\n# 3. Install dependencies: pip install openai pytest pydantic locache\n# 4. Install HDR library: cd scripts && pip install -e .\n# 5. Save this code as example.py and run: python example.py\n\n# First, import the HDR tools you need\nfrom hdr import BaseModel, llm_assert, quote, save_config\n\n# Configure your API key (get one from https://openrouter.ai)\nsave_config({\n    \"openrouter_api_key\": \"sk-or-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx\",\n    \"openrouter_model\": \"anthropic/claude-3-opus\"\n})\n\n# Define your task class\nclass SummarizeText(BaseModel):\n    original_text: str\n    summary: str\n    max_words: int = 50\n    \n    def __init__(self, **data):\n        super().__init__(**data)\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} includes all important information from {quote(self.original_text)}\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} is no more than {self.max_words} words long\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.summary)} is written in simple, easy to understand language\")\n\n# Run your task\nresult = SummarizeText(\n    original_text=\"HDR is a new Python library that makes it easy to define tasks and validate that they were completed correctly. It uses AI to check your work automatically, so you can be confident that your tasks meet all your requirements. HDR works with any LLM model and requires no complicated setup.\",\n    summary=\"HDR is a Python library that lets you define tasks and use AI to automatically validate their completion, working with any LLM model and requiring minimal setup.\",\n    max_words=30\n)\n\n# Success!\nprint(\"🎉 Task complete!\")\nprint(f\"Summary: {result.summary}\")",
        "# Simple user registration validation example\n# Requires HDR library installed (follow installation steps above)\nfrom hdr import BaseModel, llm_assert, quote\n\nclass UserRegistration(BaseModel):\n    username: str\n    email: str\n    password: str\n    \n    def __init__(self, **data):\n        super().__init__(**data)\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.username)} is 3-20 characters with only letters, numbers, and underscores\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.email)} is a valid email address\")\n        llm_assert(f\"{quote(self.password)} is at least 8 characters with uppercase, lowercase, and number\")\n\n# Valid registration example\nuser = UserRegistration(\n    username=\"john_doe123\",\n    email=\"john@example.com\",\n    password=\"SecurePass123\"\n)\n\nprint(\"✅ User registration is valid!\")"
    ]
)

